0. Introduction¶

In large cities across the world, many people use bikes as their method of transportation. Biking can help people skip heavy city traffic, is better for the environment, and is a great form of exercise. This is no exception in Seoul, South Korea. Seoul has a bike sharing program called Ttareungi where anyone can rent bikes. Its usage is about 52,000 trips per day on average, which would include both recreational use and commuting. Seoul also has encouraged residents and tourists to use bikes. Their city includes over 900 km of bike lanes and over 145,000 bike racks to make biking safer and more convenient for everyone. The main purpose of this project is to determine how different factors affect the number of rented bikes in Seoul, South Korea and to provide a way to predict the demand. We have gathered a dataset from Kaggle and implemented our own analysis and machine learning techniques to draw conclusions about what affects the rented bike count in Seoul.

This is important to answer because biking is a huge part of the lifestyle in Seoul. The bike share program will need to be as efficient as possible so that anyone in Seoul will be able to easily rent a bike without any inconveniences. By analyzing the different factors that affect the rented bike count, we will be able to predict things such as whether a certain day will have a lot of rented bikes or not. Using this, you could see what conditions in Seoul have a high rented bike count and prepare more bikes in advance so nobody is left without one.

During this tutorial, we will be going through each step we took when analyzing our topic:

  1. Data Collection
  2. Data Preprocessing
  3. Exploratory Analysis
  4. Primary Analysis
  5. Insights and Conclusions

1. Data Collection¶

The first step we took is finding a dataset that is relevant to the topic we are looking for. Kaggle is an online platform that has a wide variety of datasets for many different topics. We were able to download the dataset, which was a .csv file that included data on rented bike count in Seoul from December 1, 2017 to November 30, 2018. Each row represents one hour of data which includes the number of rented bikes, temperature statistics, what season that date represents, etc. Download the dataset here and import into Google Colab.

We’re also going to break down the Date column into multiple new columns: Year, Month, Day, and Weekday. Year, month, and day will represent the actual date and weekday will tell us the day of the week (Monday, Tuesday, etc.). This will help when we’re trying to find the relationship between these new features and rented bike count when doing our analysis. Finally, we can drop the old Date column since it will include redundant information in our new columns.

In [ ]:
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'], dayfirst=True)

df['Year'] = df['Date'].dt.year
df['Month'] = df['Date'].dt.month
df['Day'] = df['Date'].dt.day
df['Weekday'] = df['Date'].dt.day_name()

df = df.drop(['Date'], axis=1)

There are many outliers in the box plots for Rented Bike Count, Wind Speed, and Solar Radiation. However, they are representative of what occurs frequently in reality, so they are useful pieces of data. We will not worry about handling them. In particular, Rented Bike Count likely has many outliers because there are certain peak hours at which customers will rent bikes compared to other hours, which we will show later.

The reason why there are so many outliers in rainfall and snowfall is because most days there is no rainfall or snowfall so their box plots heavily centered around 0 or a value that is very close to 0.

Now we can start using statistical methods to analyze the relationships between Rented Bike Count and other attributes.

Relationship Between Seasons and Rented Bike Count¶

For our first statistical method, we are going to conduct a Kruskal-Wallis test to show the relationship between seasons and rented bike count.

Kruskal-Wallis Test (a = 0.05)¶

Ho: Median rented bike count per hour is equal across all seasons

Ha: At least one season has a different median rented bike count per hour compared to the other seasons.

In [ ]:
kruskal_results = stats.kruskal(df[df['Seasons'] == 'Spring']['Rented Bike Count'],
                                df[df['Seasons'] == 'Summer']['Rented Bike Count'],
                                df[df['Seasons'] == 'Autumn']['Rented Bike Count'],
                                df[df['Seasons'] == 'Winter']['Rented Bike Count'])

print("Spring median:", df[df['Seasons'] == 'Spring']['Rented Bike Count'].median())
print("Summer median:", df[df['Seasons'] == 'Summer']['Rented Bike Count'].median())
print("Autumn median:", df[df['Seasons'] == 'Autumn']['Rented Bike Count'].median())
print("Winter median:", df[df['Seasons'] == 'Winter']['Rented Bike Count'].median())
print("Kruskal-Wallis p-value:", kruskal_results.pvalue)

Spring median: 599.0
Summer median: 905.5
Autumn median: 856.0
Winter median: 203.0
Kruskal-Wallis p-value: 0.0

Since the p-value (around 0.0, very small) is less than the significance level a (0.05), we can reject the null hypothesis. This means that there is strong evidence for the idea that at least one season has a different median rented bike count per hour compared to the other seasons.

From our Kruskal-Wallis test, we can then apply a Post Hoc Dunn’s Test to see if any two seasons have the same median rented bike count.

Post Hoc Dunn's Test for Kruskal-Wallis¶

In [ ]:
data = [df[df['Seasons'] == 'Spring']['Rented Bike Count'],
        df[df['Seasons'] == 'Summer']['Rented Bike Count'],
        df[df['Seasons'] == 'Autumn']['Rented Bike Count'],
        df[df['Seasons'] == 'Winter']['Rented Bike Count']]

dunn_results = sp.posthoc_dunn(data).applymap(lambda x: f'{x:.4f}')
print(dunn_results)

        1       2       3       4
1  1.0000  0.0000  0.0000  0.0000
2  0.0000  1.0000  0.0001  0.0000
3  0.0000  0.0001  1.0000  0.0000
4  0.0000  0.0000  0.0000  1.0000

No two different seasons have the same median rented bike count because no two seasons have a p-value that is greater than the significance level of 0.05.

Let’s make some visuals to see that the rented bike counts across the four different seasons are indeed different.

Next, we will conduct a Mann-Whitney U Test and a Kruskal-Wallis Test to show the relationship between retained bike count and the hour of the day.

Relationship Between Rented Bike Count and Hours¶

Mann-Whitney U Test (a = 0.05)¶

Ho: The median rented bike count during daytime hours (7AM - 6:59PM) is the same as the median rented bike count during night time hours (7PM - 6:59AM).

Ha: The median rented bike count during daytime hours is different than the median rented bike count during night time hours.

In [ ]:
daytime = df[(df['Hour'] >= 7) & (df['Hour'] < 19)]['Rented Bike Count']
nighttime = df[(df['Hour'] >= 19) | (df['Hour'] < 7)]['Rented Bike Count']
res = stats.mannwhitneyu(daytime, nighttime)

print("Daytime median:", daytime.median())
print("Nighttime median:", nighttime.median())
print("p-value:", res.pvalue)

Daytime median: 761.0
Nighttime median: 326.0
p-value: 8.443038465173174e-131

Since the p-value < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. This means that the median rented bike count during daytime hours is different than the median rented bike count during night time hours.

Kruskal-Wallis Test (a = 0.05)¶

Ho: Median rented bike count is equal across all hours

Ha: At least one hour has a different median rented bike count compared to the other hours.

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import kruskal

bike_counts_by_hour = [df[df['Hour'] == hour]['Rented Bike Count'] for hour in range(24)]

stat, p = kruskal(*bike_counts_by_hour)

print(f'Kruskal-Wallis H statistic: {stat}')
print(f'p-value: {p}')

Kruskal-Wallis H statistic: 2610.4900235657055
p-value: 0.0

The Kruskal-Wallis test yielded a p-value of approximately 0.0, so we can reject the null hypothesis, suggesting that there are statistically significant differences in the median rented bike counts across the 24 hours of the day. This indicates that the number of bike rentals is not uniform throughout the day, and certain hours exhibit significantly different bike rental counts compared to others.

Using our Kruskal-Wallis test, we can conduct another Post Hoc Dunn’s Test to see what pairs of hairs don’t have a significantly median rented bike count.

Finally, we will conduct another Mann-Whitney test to show the relationship between rented bike count and visibility along with some visualizations to see what’s happening.

Relationship Between Rented Bike Count and Visibility¶

Mann-Whitney Test (a = 0.05)¶

Ho: The number of rented bikes per hour under normal visibility (greater than or equal to 1000 10m) is equal to the number of rented bikes under lower visibility (less than 1000 10m).

Ha: The number of rented bikes per hour under normal visibility days is not equal to the number of rented bikes under lower visibility.

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import mannwhitneyu

normal_visibility = df[df['Visibility (10m)'] >= 1000]

lower_visibility = df[df['Visibility (10m)'] < 1000]

stat, p = mannwhitneyu(normal_visibility['Rented Bike Count'], lower_visibility['Rented Bike Count'])

print("Median Number of Rented Bikes Under Normal Visibility:", df[df['Visibility (10m)'] >= 1000]['Rented Bike Count'].median())
print("Median Number of Rented Bikes Under Lower Visibility:", df[df['Visibility (10m)'] < 1000]['Rented Bike Count'].median())
print(f'Mann-Whitney U statistic: {stat}')
print(f'p-value: {p}')

Median Number of Rented Bikes Under Normal Visibility: 642.0
Median Number of Rented Bikes Under Lower Visibility: 342.5
Mann-Whitney U statistic: 8976552.0
p-value: 1.3469959624273748e-77

The p-value is much smaller than the alpha level of 0.05, indicating that there is a statistically significant difference in the number of rented bikes between days with normal visibility (defined here as visibility at or above 10000 meters) and days with lower visibility (defined as visibility below 10000 meters). In other words, the test results suggest that the number of rented bike counts per hour under normal visibility is significantly different from the distribution of rented bikes per hour under lower visibility. This implies that visibility could indeed affect the number of bikes rented per hour.

Let's make some visualizations to show our results from our Mann-Whitney test.

The violin and box plots provided illustrate the distribution of rented bike counts under different visibility conditions. The violin plot reveals that the distribution for normal visibility is broader with a higher density around the median, suggesting that higher bike counts are more common when visibility is good. The "Lower" visibility category, on the other hand, has a more tapered distribution, which suggests a narrower range of bike counts around the median. In the violin plots, the kernel density estimation on each side of the gray line (which represents the median) shows the distribution shape of the rented bike counts. The wider sections of the violin plot indicate a higher probability density, meaning it is more likely for members of the population (rented bike counts) to have values in that range. Conversely, the skinnier sections represent a lower probability density, indicating it is less likely for the rented bike counts to fall within those ranges. The box plot supports the visualization made by the violin plot, showing a higher median rented bike count for normal visibility compared to lower visibility, with a larger interquartile range indicating greater variability on days with normal visibility. Both plots display outliers, indicating occasional days with unusually high bike counts in both visibility categories.

Conclusions from Exploratory Analysis¶

The analysis of the Seoul Bike Sharing Demand dataset reveals that bike rental demand is significantly influenced by seasonal changes, time of day, and weather conditions, particularly visibility. Given the presence of outliers and overrepresented features like rainfall and snowfall, a sophisticated regression modeling approach, such as linear regression, random forests, or gradient boosting, is recommended to accurately predict hourly bike rental demand. While linear regression can capture the overall trends and relationships between the features and the target variable, random forests and gradient boosting are preferred due to their ability to handle complex, non-linear relationships and outliers, which are inherent in the dataset. The insights indicate that bike rental patterns are not only subject to typical daily fluctuations, with higher demand during daytime and specific peak hours, but also to environmental factors and seasonal variations, underscoring the necessity for a predictive model that can adeptly navigate these dynamics to optimize bike fleet management and enhance user satisfaction in Seoul's bike-sharing system. The choice of random forests or gradient boosting is further justified by their robustness to outliers, capability to model non-linear relationships, and provision of insights into feature importance, which are crucial for understanding and predicting the nuanced patterns of bike rental demand. Moreover, their flexibility and adaptability make them suitable for the dataset's mix of continuous and categorical variables, and their proven prediction accuracy ensures that they can effectively meet the challenges presented by the Seoul Bike Sharing Demand dataset, thereby supporting efficient bike fleet management and improving user experience. However, linear regression remains a valuable baseline model that can provide interpretable coefficients and help identify the overall impact of each feature on the bike rental demand.

4. Primary Analysis¶

Let’s now hop into our primary analysis. We will first apply feature engineering to prepare our data for machine learning.

Feature Engineering¶

To start off, notice that some of our columns like Holiday, Hour, Month, and Weekday are categorical variables. To utilize these features, we have to apply one hot encoding to transform them into numerical values for our model. We will also drop irrelevant columns like Year, Day, and Seasons. This is because the patterns in Rental Bike Count from these columns are sufficiently accounted for with the Month column. It provides information more frequently than on a yearly basis; days of the month only offers redundant information on what kind of day it is (holiday, weekday, etc.); seasons depend on the time of year or in other words what month it is.

In [ ]:
# Applying one-hot encoding to categorical variables and dropping irrelevant columns
df2 = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['Holiday', 'Hour', 'Month', 'Weekday'])
df2 = df2.drop(columns=['Year', 'Day', 'Seasons'])
df2 = df2.astype(int)

To ensure our data is scaled similarly, we can apply log transformations.

In [ ]:
# Applying log transformations
df2['Rented Bike Count'] = (df2['Rented Bike Count'] - df2['Rented Bike Count'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Temperature(°C)'] = (df2['Temperature(°C)'] - df2['Temperature(°C)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Humidity(%)'] = (df2['Humidity(%)'] - df2['Humidity(%)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Wind speed (m/s)'] = (df2['Wind speed (m/s)'] - df2['Wind speed (m/s)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Visibility (10m)'] = (df2['Visibility (10m)'] - df2['Visibility (10m)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Dew point temperature(°C)'] = (df2['Dew point temperature(°C)'] - df2['Dew point temperature(°C)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Solar Radiation (MJ/m2)'] = (df2['Solar Radiation (MJ/m2)'] - df2['Solar Radiation (MJ/m2)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Rainfall(mm)'] = (df2['Rainfall(mm)'] - df2['Rainfall(mm)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)
df2['Snowfall (cm)'] = (df2['Snowfall (cm)'] - df2['Snowfall (cm)'].min() + 1).transform(np.log)

5. Insights and Conclusions¶

In conclusion, this project was an analysis of bike rental demand in Seoul, South Korea, with the aim of understanding the factors influencing bike rental demand and developing predictive models to forecast bike rental demand accurately.

Our exploratory analysis revealed significant correlations between bike rental count and factors like seasons, time of day, and visibility. Using statistical tests such as the Kruskal-Wallis test and Mann-Whitney U test, we validated our conclusions regarding the impact of these factors on bike rental counts. These tests provided strong evidence supporting our findings and highlighted the importance of considering these factors in predicting bike rental demand accurately.

Building on our exploratory analysis, we developed predictive models using linear regression and random forest regression techniques. While our linear regression model provided a baseline understanding of the relationships between features and bike rental count, our random forest regression model offered superior predictive performance. These models have the potential to assist bike rental operators in optimizing inventory management, pricing strategies, and operational decisions to meet demand efficiently.

The Random Forest Regression model and the Gradient Boosting Regression model has demonstrated strong predictive performance on the Seoul Bike Sharing dataset, with a Mean Squared Error of 0.1637788495116745 and an $r^{2}$ Score of 0.8704339880237051 for random forest and Mean Squared Error of 0.21430818270415072 and an $r^{2}$ Score of 0.830460058489514 for gradient boosting, indicating their ability to accurately forecast bike rental demand based on factors such as weather conditions, time of day, and day of the week. The graphs of each respective model also show that many of the points are concentrated near the estimated regression line indicating the random forest and gradient boosting regression models fit the data well and the models' predictions are quite accurate. By leveraging the feature importance insights provided by the model, bike rental operators can optimize bike distribution across stations, adjust pricing strategies, schedule maintenance activities, and communicate expected bike availability to customers, ultimately transforming their operations by enabling data-driven decision-making and improving overall efficiency.

We notice that after running feature importances on both the random forest and gradient boosting regression models that temperature, humidity, and rainfall are some of the biggest factors in predicting bike rental demand Seoul, South Korea. While both regression models provide the similar insights into most influential predictors, the feature importance measures differ between the two methods. Random Forest uses a measure called Mean Decrease in Impurity (MDI), which is based on the decrease in node impurity weighted by the probability of reaching that node. Gradient Boosting, on the other hand, can use various feature importance measures, such as Gain (the improvement in loss function brought by a feature) and Cover (the number of samples affected by a feature) all of which are then averaged across all trees in the model to calculate feature importance. Since both the random forest regression model and the gradient boosting regression model indicate the similar results, we can reliably say that temperature, humidity, and rainfall are the most influential predictors of Seoul's bike renting demand.

Overall, we can use this data and analysis to provide Seoul with more information about the number of rented bikes they may expect to have in a given day based on various factors like temperature, humidity, and the day of the week. This can help Seoul create a more efficient bike program for everyone in the city to use.
